{% block ABSTRACT %}
  <section id="abstract">
    <p>The EU-GDPR extension extends the [[[DPV]]] to provide concepts such as legal bases, rights, and data transfer tools based on the [[[GDPR]]]. The canonical URL for EU-GDPR extension is <a href="https://w3id.org/dpv/legal/eu/gdpr">https://w3id.org/dpv/legal/eu/gdpr</a>, the namespace for terms is <a href="https://w3id.org/dpv/legal/eu/gdpr#"><code>https://w3id.org/dpv/legal/eu/gdpr#</code></a>, the suggested prefix is <code>eu-gdpr</code>, and this document along with source and releases are available at <a href="https://github.com/w3c/dpv">https://github.com/w3c/dpv</a>.</p>
    {{ sotd(data[vocab_name+'-metadata']) }}
    {{ dpv_document_family(document='eu-gdpr-spec') }}
  </section>
{% endblock ABSTRACT %}
{% block INTRODUCTION %}
  <section id="introduction">
    <h2>Introduction</h2>
      <figure>
	<object type="image/svg+xml" data="../../../diagrams/gdpr_Overview.svg">      
	  <img src="../../../diagrams/gdpr_Overview.svg">
	</object>
	<figcaption>GDPR Extension extending DPV core concepts. Blue boxes are placeholders for concepts that are further detailed. See corresponding section in this document for more information. <a href="../../../diagrams/gdpr_Overview.svg">Click here to open diagram in new window</a>.</figcaption>
      </figure>

    <p>The [[EU-GDPR]] extension provides concepts extending the [[DPV]] to represent information requirements from the [[GDPR]]. It enables the use of DPV to represent use-cases that are regulated by the GDPR, such as using specific legal bases defined in the GDPR, or to represent the applicability of rights, or requirements for conducting data protection impact assessments. It also enables representing practicalities such as organisations and their 'establishments' in the EU, data breach reporting and impact assessments, and data transfer tools. In particular, the [[EU-GDPR]] extension provides the following:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="#vocab-legal-basis">Legal Bases</a> for processing personal data as defined in Articles 6 and 9 (special categories of personal data) and 45-49 (data transfer)</li>
      <li><a href="#vocab-principles">Principles</a> as defined in Article 5</li>
      <li><a href="#vocab-rights">Data Subject Rights</a> as defined in Articles 7, 12-22, and 77, as well as notices required to be provided</li>
      <li><a href="#vocab-legal-basis-rights-mapping">mapping between Rights and Legal Bases</a> which indicates which right must be provided for each legal basis</li>
      <li><a href="#vocab-data-transfers">Data Transfer Tools</a> as defiend by <a href="https://edpb.europa.eu/system/files/2021-06/edpb_recommendations_202001vo.2.0_supplementarymeasurestransferstools_en.pdf">EDPB Recommendations 01/2020 on Supplementary Measures and Transfer Tools</a> </li>
      <li><a href="#vocab-dpia">Data Protection Impact Assessment (DPIA)</a> information as defined in Article 35, such as necessity to conduct a DPIA, indicating the findings of DPIA in terms of risk levels and impacts, and the outcomes of DPIAs regarding continuation of processing</li>
      <li><a href="#vocab-data-breach">Data Breach</a> information such as types of breaches, notices, reporting requirements, and risk levels</li>
      <li><a href="#vocab-entities-establishment">Establishment &amp; Authorities</a> to indicate aspects such as 'main' etablishment of an organisation, and to indicate role of DPAs as 'lead' supervisory authority</li>
      <li><a href="#vocab-compliance">Compliance</a> to express whether the specific process or context is compliant with the GDPR</li>
    </ul>
  </section>
{% endblock INTRODUCTION %}
{% block VOCAB %}
  <section id="vocab-legal-basis">
    <h2>Legal Basis</h2>
    <p>GDPR Article 6 specifies that it is mandatory for every processing to have one (or more) legal basis that justifies its compliance. These are represented as <a href="#vocab-legal-basis-core">Core Legal Basis</a> concepts by extending relevant <code>dpv:LegalBasis</code> concepts, such as for consent or contract. Similarly, Article 9 legal basis are represented as <a href="#vocab-legal-basis-special">Special Category Legal Basis</a>, and those from Articles 45, 46, and 49 are represented as instances of <code>dpv:DataTransferLegalBasis</code> to create <a href="#vocab-legal-basis-data-transfer">Data Transfer Legal Basis</a>.</p>
    <aside class="note" title="DPV does not define validity of legal basis">
      <p>[[DPV]] and the [[EU-GDPR]] extension represents legal basis and their use as well as validity as concepts, and evaluating compliance or assessing the validity of specific instances is not in the scope of this work. For example, determining whether an instance of given consent is valid, or the appropriateness of a legal basis for its application in a use-case. The DPVCG is interested in providing "helpful assistance" to support such tasks through its concepts, and welcomes discussions and contributions for the same. Planned work regarding this includes providing 'hints' or 'suggestions' for which [[EU-GDPR]] legal basis can be used for specific [[DPV]] purposes based on authoritative guidance and case law.</p>
    </aside>
    <aside class="example" title="Expressing GDPR consent and contract as the legal basis">
      <p>This example demonstrates using the EU-GDPR to indicate Art.6-1b contract as the legal basis, and using Art.9-2a explicit consent as the legal basis.</p>
      <pre class="nohighlight"><code>ex:PDH1 a dpv:Process ;
  dpv:hasPersonalData pd:EmailAddress ;
  dpv:hasLegalBasis eu-gdpr:A6-1-b . # contract performance

ex:PDH2 a dpv:Process ;
  dpv:hasPersonalData pd:BloodType ; # special category
  dpv:hasLegalBasis eu-gdpr:A9-2-a . # explicit consent
      </code></pre>
    </aside>
    <aside class="example" title="Expressing legal basis using both DPV and EU-GDPR">
      <p>This example shows how DPV concepts are general/abstract notions of legal basis, and the use of extensions such as EU-GDPR enables expressing legally defined legal basis for accurate representation of requirements. It first represents a process which uses DPV consent to indicate, in general, that consent is the legal basis for the process, and EU-GDPR to specificly indicate that the consent is as defined in Art.6-1a. The second process demonstrates declaring explicitly expressed consent as the legal basis with GDPR as the applicable law, but no explicit reference to a particular clause within GDPR. The implication of this is that an assessment is necessary to determine how the consent must be interpreted within GDPR's framework as the personal data involved is of special category. Therefore, where GDPR is known to be applied, we recommend specifying the EU-GDPR defined legal basis by itself or in addition to the general legal basis from DPV.</p>
      <pre class="nohighlight"><code>ex:PDH1 a dpv:Process ;
  dpv:hasLegalBasis dpv:ExpressedConsent ; # general legal basis
  dpv:hasLegalBasis eu-gdpr:A6-1-a . # GDPR specific consent

# This is okay to do, but is not legally complete.
# Suggested to (also) use eu-gdpr:A9-2-a as the legal basis to indicate
# that the explicitly expressed consent is asserted to be as per GDPR.
ex:PDH2 a dpv:Process ;
  dpv:hasPersonalData pd:BloodType ; # special category
  dpv:hasLegalBasis dpv:ExplicitlyExpressedConsent ;
  dpv:hasApplicableLaw eu:GDPR . # which consent as per to GDPR?
      </code></pre>
    </aside>

