  <section id="vocab-entities">
    <h2>Establishment and Authorities</h2>
    <section id="vocab-entities-establishment">
      <h3>Establishment</h3>
      <p>The concept 'establishment' is defined in the GPDR in Article 4-16 as 'main establishment' which is used to determine who will be the 'lead' supervisory authority responsible. An establishment in this context can be a subsidiary, a division or branch, or other forms of corporate structures through which multi-national corporations and organisations operate. To support representation of this, [[EU-GDPR]] defines the concept [=Establishment=], and extends it as [=MainEstablishment=] to indicate which establishment is the 'main'. To indicate that there is only a single establishment and no other locations are involved, the concept [=SingleEstablishment=] is provided.</p>
      <p>Establishments are indicated by using the relation [=hasEstablishment=]. Main establishment is associated by using the relation [=isMainEstablishmentFor=], or the main establishment can be indicated using [=hasMainEstablishment=]. To represent organisation structures such as subsidiaries, the relation <code>dpv:hasSubsidiary</code> and <code>dpv:isSubsidiaryOf</code> can be reused.</p>
      <aside class="example" title="Indicating Main Establishment of Organisation for GDPR">
        <p>This example shows the use of EU-GDPR to represent the main and other establishments associated with an organisation. The example uses CompanyX, established in the USA, as a fictional company which is headquartered in Ireland as X-IE and has subsidiaries in Netherlands (X-NL) and Luxembourg (X-LU). The main establishment for CompanyX in EU is X-IE. Another organisation called CompanyY is also headquartered in Ireland but does not have any other establishments - it is thus declared as a single establishment. The locations are defined using the LOC extension.</p>
        <pre class="nohighlight"><code>ex:CompanyX a dpv:Organisation ;
  dpv:hasLocation loc:US ;
  eu-gdpr:hasMainEstablishment ex:X-IE ;
  eu-gdpr:hasEstablishment ex:X-NL, ex:X-LU .

ex:X-IE a dpv:Organisation, dpv:Subsidiary, eu-gdpr:Establishment ;
  dpv:isSubsidiaryOf ex:CompanyX ;
  eu-gdpr:isMainEstablishmentFor ex:CompanyX ;
  dpv:hasLocation loc:IE .

ex:X-NL a dpv:Organisation, dpv:Subsidiary, eu-gdpr:Establishment ;
  dpv:isSubsidiaryOf ex:CompanyX ;
  dpv:hasLocation loc:NL .

ex:X-LU a dpv:Organisation, dpv:Subsidiary, eu-gdpr:Establishment ;
  dpv:isSubsidiaryOf ex:CompanyX ;
  dpv:hasLocation loc:LU .

ex:CompanyY a dpv:Orgnanisation, eu-gdpr:SingleEstablishment ;
  dpv:hasLocation loc:IE .
        </code></pre>
      </aside>
      {{ list_hierarchy(modules['entities']['classes'], head='dpv:Organisation') }}
    </section>
    <section id="vocab-entities-authorities">
      <h3>Authorities</h3>
      <p>GDPR has a cross-border procedure for handling of compliance and investigations as the authorities are defined at a national level (in addition to supra- and intra- authorities). As part of this, an investigation involving multiple authorities requires establishing which authority is the 'lead' with the others categorised as 'concerned' authorities. The 'lead' authority may be different from the 'local' authority which is defined based on where the organisation is established or has its main establishment. To represent these cases, the [[EU-GDPR]] defines [=LeadSupervisoryAuthority=], [=ConcernedSupervisoryAuthority=], and [=LocalSupervisoryAuthority=] concepts. To associate them, the relations [=hasLeadSA=], [=hasConcernedSA=], and [=hasLocalSA=] are provided.</p>
      <aside class="example" title="Indicating lead and concerned supervisory authorities for a data breach investigation">
        <p>This example shows the use of EU-GDPR extension to represent involvement of authorities in a 'lead' and 'concerned' role for a data breach incident. The data breach is associated with CompanyX as the data controller, and the Irish DPA is both the lead and local authority with the German DPA also involved. The declaration of DPAs uses the extensions LEGAL-IE for Ireland and LEGAL-DE for Germany.</p>
        <pre class="nohighlight"><code>ex:DBR1 a eu-gdpr:DataBreachReport ;
  dpv:hasDataController ex:CompanyX ;
  eu-gdpr:hasLeadSA legal-ie:DPA-IE ;
  eu-gdpr:hasLocalSA legal-ie:DPA-IE ;
  eu-gdpr:hasConcernedSA legal-de:DPA-DE .
        </code></pre>
      </aside>
      {{ list_hierarchy(modules['entities']['classes'], head='dpv:DataProtectionAuthority') }}
    </section>
  </section>

  <section id="vocab-compliance">
    <h2>Compliance</h2>
    <p>The concepts in this section reflect the status of processing operations being in <i>compliance with GDPR</i>, by extending the <code>ComplianceStatus</code> from DPV for GDPR. It does not define the requirements for compliance itself. To indicate these, the relation <code>dpv:hasLawfulness</code> can be used.</p>
    <aside class="example" title="Indicating status of GDPR lawfulness">
      <p>This example shows the use of EU-GDPR to indicate the state of GDPR lawfulness associated with two processes. The first is asserted to be compliant, while the compliance status for the second is unknown at the moment. Both processes assert the applicability of GDPR for brevity.</p>
      <pre class="nohighlight"><code>ex:PDH1 a dpv:Process ;
  dpv:hasApplicableLaw legal-eu:GDPR ;
  dpv:hasLawfulness eu-gdpr:GDPRCompliant .

ex:PDH2 a dpv:Process ;
  dpv:hasApplicableLaw legal-eu:GDPR ;
  dpv:hasLawfulness eu-gdpr:GDPRComplianceUnknown .
      </code></pre>
    </aside>
    {{ list_hierarchy(modules['compliance']['classes']) }}
  </section>

  <section id="vocabulary">
<h2>Vocabulary Index</h2>
